04425nam a22006135i 9780812298338DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122983387 a10.9783/97808122983382doi  a(DE-B1597)590734  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0020002bisacsh1 aGillette, Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Paradox of Urban Revitalization :bProgress and Poverty in America's Postindustrial Era /cHoward Gillette. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b30 b/w, 2 maps, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe City in the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Captives of the Old Paradigm -- tChapter 1. Baltimore: Despite Multiple Rebirths, a City Still Divided -- tChapter 2. Detroit: Despite a Visionary Strategic Plan, a City Still Depressed -- tChapter 3. Camden: Despite Massive Business Incentives, Still a City of Limited Opportunity -- tPart II. Shifting Ground -- tChapter 4. Milwaukee: Beyond the New Urbanism, Questions of Equity and Justice -- tChapter 5. New Haven: In a “Model City” Dominated by Eds and Meds, Still Contested Development -- tChapter 6. Washington, D.C.: In Chocolate City, a Fight to Hold On -- tPart III. Breaking Through -- tChapter 7. Oakland: What Resistance Can Achieve -- tChapter 8. Pittsburgh: Where Equity Seeks to Catch Up with Innovation -- tChapter 9. Newark: The Hard Road to Inclusive Growth -- tConclusion -- tNote -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the twenty-first century, cities in the United States that had suffered most the shift to a postindustrial era entered a period widely proclaimed as an urban renaissance. From Detroit to Newark to Oakland and elsewhere commentators saw cities rising again. Yet revitalization generated a second urban crisis marked by growing inequality and civil unrest reminiscent of the upheavals associated with the first urban crisis in the mid-twentieth century. The urban poor and residents of color have remained very much at a disadvantage in the face of racially biased capital investments, narrowing options for affordable housing, and mass incarceration. In profiling nine cities grappling with challenges of the twenty-first century, author Howard Gillette, Jr. evaluates the uneven efforts to secure racial and class equity as city fortunes have risen. Charting the tension between the practice of corporate subsidy and efforts to assure social justice, The Paradox of Urban Revitalization assesses the course of urban politics and policy over the past half century, before the COVID-19 pandemic upended everything, and details prospects for achieving greater equity in the years ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh  aPublic Policy.  aUrban Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229833840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812298338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812298338/original  a978-3-11-076767-4  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK